by Convallaria » Sat Aug 22, 2020 7:58 pm

According to the culture factbook, Godulans have had somewhat of a problem with regards to neo-nazi subversives in the past. They consisted of large numbers with an established foundation, which led to fairly strict responses against them. These days, the nazi sympathizers are all but gone, but their former presence serves as an important reminder to the Godulans as to the importance of order.

This is pretty interesting, the exact details with regard to their disappearance is vague, but I can only assume based off the allusions described within that it involved something along the lines of a supercharged atomic bombardment times a million.

AN: Acharet places a great emphasis on its military, and strives to ensure that its enlisted members are well equipped with the best that technology has to offer. Conscription is utilised, but luckily for the military, troops are generally very motivated and proud, with faith serving an important role in keeping spirits high. In fact, each unit usually has at least one chaplain on duty to help service this demand.

Very inspiring!

by Convallaria » Sun Aug 23, 2020 6:33 am

In this somewhat primitive, anti state society, the modern conveniences that we take for granted have all but disintegrated, leaving a nomadic group of morally numbed free-thinkers, and Kotera is simply another one of them, writing to ensure their stories are kept alive. Spiritually speaking, he's transcendentally philosophical in a near-sociopathic old-fashioned way, almost like the kind of character you'd see written into a Stanley Kubrick movie. The reminder of the indispensability of human nature even in a post-traditional world setting is fairly enlightening, and I enjoyed this read.

English is the lingua franca and the official language used in business, government, law and education within Convallaria. The Constitution of Convallaria and all government legislations are written in English, and interpreters are required if a language other than English is used in the Convallarian courts. Statutory corporations conduct their businesses in English, while any official documents written in a non-English language such as French, Spanish, or Yiddish are typically translated into English to be accepted for use.
